The stage of plums
LONDON – Prime Minister Theresa May faces a daunting task: implementing the UK’s – or, more precisely, England and Wales’ – electorate’s mandate to “leave the EU” and managing the far-reaching consequences of that process.
The challenge she faces outshines those of all previous prime ministers in recent years.
But she might have the ability to complete this task.
No one should underestimate Mei.
Like German Chancellor Angela Merkel, who has already demonstrated courage in a series of crises, all the tools necessary to get the job done are in May's hands.
She is clever and resilient, and has no patience for nonsense.
She possesses a strong sense of public service along with equally strong values.
She is not constrained by any ideology, is very skilled at seizing control, and operates within self-drawn boundaries to ensure she is familiar with the issues at hand.
In most of the battles she participated in, Mei emerged victorious, showing no mercy to those who had dealt with her underhandedly.
But she has few enemies within the party and is quite popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination - one that she needs to make full use of to lead the Brexit process in Britain.
The Brexit process has indeed begun.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland vote in favor of remaining in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot be undone.
She repeatedly stated that "Brexit means Brexit," and her ministerial colleagues also agreed with her view.
But Mei has not yet given a precise definition of Brexit.
This task is very difficult to complete.
Imagine someone saying to you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare food for you.
It's difficult to know precisely what you will be eating.
A Northern Irish "Ulster fry" — eggs, bacon, pork sausages, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes — with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you may feel very differently about various possible combinations.
The same applies to the UK's Brexit.
Some may focus primarily on preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
And there are those who are more focused on securing single-market access rights.
But unlike with breakfast, Britain cannot order a little bit of everything from the menu.
The reality that the Leave camp often ignores is that the EU will not offer Britain any benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to appeal to public opinion or punish the UK for not joining the EU (though such inflammatory rhetoric is sometimes prevalent, as when UK Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson referred to "Hitler-style imperialism").
On the contrary, we Britons often forget that everyone – including the EU and all its member states – has political or commercial interests that they swear to protect.
For Rishi Sunak, the core challenge over the coming months will be to determine Britain's objectives following the difficult negotiations that are set to begin on its relationship with the EU (and, in the realm of trade, with the world more broadly) based on reality?
Given the scope of the agenda (there are at least six major themes that need to be negotiated separately), the negotiation process could take several years to complete.
(When the negotiations are completed, my 11-year-old granddaughter might already be starting college!)
We must prioritize clearly to prevent the negotiations from dragging on any longer.
The goal, of course, is to strike a balance between allowing British exports of goods and services (especially financial services) into other European countries and restricting EU citizens’ access to the UK.
The more one side gains in one area, the more it needs to give up in other areas.
Mei needs to fully utilize her knowledge, skills, and political capital to ensure the rationality of the negotiation outcomes.
But even if she were to successfully achieve her goals, she would still find that discontented people would not be just a part of them — such results are inevitable — but all of them.
This willacerbate another major challenge facing the Conservative government: widening the chasm in British society that Brexit has brought to the fore.
Blue-collar workers in the north and midlands of England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum, and they have long been distant from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by its so-called代理人—the EU.
Large metropolitan areas in England — particularly London — may have benefited significantly from globalization, but they have not reaped any of these benefits.
Due to a lack of confidence in the leftist leader Jeremy Corbyn's Labour Party, many blue-collar workers ultimately fell prey to the populist promises of Leave campaigners.
They said, "We will reverse globalization."
"The plan is to get rid of immigrants pressing down wages and to redirect the millions of pounds that were going to the EU into public services."
They pledged that Brexit would allow Britain to recapture a safer and more prosperous past.
The Brexiters cannot genuinely deliver on these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can it be used to cut off immigration from the EU.
Any such move would only destroy British businesses.
Even if an economic downturn leads to a decrease in immigration, the workers who voted for Brexit may still feel disillusioned, finding that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and that pressures on public services remain high.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The UK's Brexit referendum has already unleashed a storm of uncontrollable populist sentiment.
Just as Donald Trump is ineffectual in improving the lot of American blue-collar voters, no matter how the situation may appear, Brexit offers no benefit to those who chose it.
Despite its many advantages, such challenges may still be difficult for Mercury to overcome.
